sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Load Of RstrtMgr.DLL By An Uncommon Process
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the load of RstrtMgr DLL (Restart Manager) by an uncommon process.
This library has been used during ransomware campaigns to kill processes that would prevent file encryption by locking them (e.g. Conti ransomware, Cactus ransomware). It has also recently been seen used by the BiBi wiper for Windows.
It could also be used for anti-analysis purposes by shut downing specific processes.

T1003.description: Adversaries may attempt to dump credentials to obtain account login and credential material, normally in the form of a hash or a clear text password, from the operating system and software.
Tries to harvest and steal ftp login credentials
Tries to harvest and steal browser information (history, passwords, etc)

T1539.description: An adversary may steal web application or service session cookies and use them to gain access to web applications or Internet services as an authenticated user without needing credentials.

T1555.description: Adversaries may search for common password storage locations to obtain user credentials.

T1552.description: Adversaries may search compromised systems to find and obtain insecurely stored credentials.

T1555.003.description: Adversaries may acquire credentials from web browsers by reading files specific to the target browser.

T1552.001.description: Adversaries may search local file systems and remote file shares for files containing insecurely stored credentials.

T1114.description: Adversaries may target user email to collect sensitive information.
Tries to search for mail accounts

T1005.description: Adversaries may search local system sources, such as file systems and configuration files or local databases, to find files of interest and sensitive data prior to Exfiltration.
Found many strings related to Crypto-Wallets (likely being stolen)
Tries to harvest and steal ftp login credentials
Tries to harvest and steal browser information (history, passwords, etc)

T1082.description: An adversary may attempt to get detailed information about the operating system and hardware, including version, patches, hotfixes, service packs, and architecture.
Queries the volume information (name, serial number etc) of a device
Checks if Microsoft Office is installed
Queries information about the installed CPU (vendor, model number etc)

T1057.description: Adversaries may attempt to get information about running processes on a system.
Queries a list of all running processes

T1012.description: Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to gather information about the system, configuration, and installed software.

T1518.description: Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of software and software versions that are installed on a system or in a cloud environment.

T1071.description: Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
C2 URLs / IPs found in malware configuration
Downloads files from webservers via HTTP

T1106.description: Adversaries may interact with the native OS application programming interface (API) to execute behaviors.

T1055.description: Adversaries may inject code into processes in order to evade process-based defenses as well as possibly elevate privileges.

T1027.description: Adversaries may attempt to make an executable or file difficult to discover or analyze by encrypting, encoding, or otherwise obfuscating its contents on the system or in transit.

T1027.002.description: Adversaries may perform software packing or virtual machine software protection to conceal their code.

T1485.description: Adversaries may destroy data and files on specific systems or in large numbers on a network to interrupt availability to systems, services, and network resources.

T1059.description: Sample may offer command line options, please run it with the command line option cookbook (it's possible that the command line switches require additional characters like)
Sample might require command line arguments, analyze it with the command line cookbook

T1036.description: Creates files inside the user directory

T1562.001.description: Creates guard pages, often used to prevent reverse engineering and debugging

T1518.001.description: May try to detect the virtual machine to hinder analysis (VM artifact strings found in memory)

T1105.description: Downloads files from webservers via HTTP
